Hence, it suffices to show it is sober. Suppose now we have an irreducible closed set C. Consider the following procedure:
Pick some x_0\in C;
If \downarrow x_i \subsetneq C, then pick x_{i+1}\in C - \downarrow x_i. If this process never terminate, then we have an infinite strictly increasing chain of elements x_0 < x_1 < \cdots , contradictory to image finiteness of X. Hence, we must have C = \downarrow x_i for some i, which implies C has the generic point x_i.

